            <fr:title text="Principal ideal domains are unique factorization domains">Principal ideal domains are unique factorization domains</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Dummit and Foote <fr:link href="/dummit-2004-abstract/" title="Abstract Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/dummit-2004-abstract/" display-uri="dummit-2004-abstract" type="local">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Theorem 8.3.14</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/ra-001M/" title="Principal Ideal Domain" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-001M/" display-uri="ra-001M" type="local">Principal Ideal Domain</fr:link>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  R]]></fr:tex> be a nonzero non-invertible element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists <fr:link href="/ra-001U/" title="Irreducible element" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-001U/" display-uri="ra-001U" type="local">irreducible elements</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{1},…,p_{n}\in  R]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a=p_{1}(…)p_{n}]]></fr:tex>. Further, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{1},…,q_{m}\in  R]]></fr:tex> are irreducible and such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a=q_{1}(…)q_{m}]]></fr:tex> then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m=n]]></fr:tex> and for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i=1,…,n]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{i}=u_{i}p_{i}]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in R^{\times }]]></fr:tex> is a unit.</html:p><html:p>In other words, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/ra-001Z/" title="Unique Factorization Domain" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-001Z/" display-uri="ra-001Z" type="local">Unique Factorization Domain</fr:link>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>18</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>There are two claims: (1) there is a factorization, and (2) the factorization is unique.</html:p>
<html:p><html:strong>Claim 1: Existence of a factorization.</html:strong> Assume for contradiction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  R]]></fr:tex> does not have a factorization. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ua\in  R]]></fr:tex> does not have a factorization for any unit <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in R^{\times }]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>We setup a set
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[S:=\{(r)\mathrel {\triangleleft } R\mid  r\hbox { does not have a factorization into irreducibles}\}.]]></fr:tex>
Assume for contradiction that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\neq \emptyset ]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(a)]]></fr:tex> be a maximal element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> by <fr:link href="/zorn's-lemma/" title="Zorn's lemma" uri="http://localhost:8000/zorn's-lemma/" display-uri="zorn's-lemma" type="local">Zorn's lemma</fr:link>. We have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is not irreducible, so by definition we can write it as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a=xy]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\notin R^{\times }]]></fr:tex> are not units, so
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[(a)\subset (x)]]></fr:tex>
and
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[(a)\subset (y)]]></fr:tex>
are proper subsets.</html:p>
<html:p>But since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(a)]]></fr:tex> is a maximal element of a chain, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x)\notin  S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(y)\notin  S]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> have a factorization. This gives us a contradiction, which means our assumption <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\neq \emptyset ]]></fr:tex> is wrong. We conclude <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S=\emptyset ]]></fr:tex>. Hence we've proven the factorization of elements exists.</html:p>
<html:p><html:strong>Claim 2: Uniqueness of factorization.</html:strong> This may be proven in many, many ways. Assume for contradiction this is not true, so we may factorize
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\prod ^{n}_{i}p_{i}=\prod ^{m}_{j}q_{j},]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is minimal (i.e., the factorization <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\prod ^{n}_{i}p_{i}]]></fr:tex> is the smallest possible factorization with fewest possible factors).</html:p>
<html:p>We have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq 1]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p=p_{1}]]></fr:tex> divides <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |}\prod  q_{j}]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j_{0}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} q_{j_{0}}]]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{i}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{j}]]></fr:tex> are all prime and irreducible. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p=uq_{j_{0}}]]></fr:tex> for some unit <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in R^{\times }]]></fr:tex> (since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{j_{0}}]]></fr:tex> are irreducible). Then
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[p_{1}\prod ^{n}_{i=2}p_{i}=(uq_{j_{0}})u^{-1}\prod ^{m}_{j\neq  j_{0}}q_{j}]]></fr:tex>
which implies
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\prod ^{n}_{i=2}p_{i}=u^{-1}\prod ^{m}_{j\neq  j_{0}}q_{j}.]]></fr:tex>
This contradicts the assumption that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\prod ^{n}_{i=1}p_{i}]]></fr:tex> is the minimal factorization.</html:p>
<html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
