            <fr:title text="Existence of Maximal Ideals">Existence of Maximal Ideals</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Krull's <fr:link href="/krull-1929-idealtheorie/" title="Idealtheorie in Ringen ohne Endlichkeitsbedingung" uri="http://localhost:8000/krull-1929-idealtheorie/" display-uri="krull-1929-idealtheorie" type="local">Idealtheorie in Ringen ohne Endlichkeitsbedingung</fr:link> (1929)</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\neq 0]]></fr:tex> be a nonzero unital <fr:link href="/ring-0001/" title="Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ring-0001/" display-uri="ring-0001" type="local">Ring</fr:link>. Then there exists a <fr:link href="/ra-001C/" title="Maximal ideal" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-001C/" display-uri="ra-001C" type="local">maximal ideal</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M\mathrel {\triangleleft } R]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>The typical proof offered is: consider the lattice of proper ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> ordered by inclusion. There exists at least one ideal of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> (e.g., the <fr:link href="/ra-0013/" title="Trivial ideal" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-0013/" display-uri="ra-0013" type="local">Trivial ideal</fr:link>). Then <fr:link href="/zorn's-lemma/" title="Zorn's lemma" uri="http://localhost:8000/zorn's-lemma/" display-uri="zorn's-lemma" type="local">Zorn's lemma</fr:link> implies there exists a maximal element of a chain containing the trivial ideal.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 

 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>(1) This is often called "Krull's theorem", which is unfortunate because there are about a half dozen different results in ring theory called "Krull's theorem".</html:p>
<html:p>(2) The condition that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is unital is really critical. For example, we can turn any additive group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> into a nonunital ring by defining multiplication <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\star  y=0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in  R]]></fr:tex>. There is no maximal ideal for such a ring</html:p>
<html:p>(3) In ZF set theory, this theorem implies the axiom of choice. Hodges first proved it. For a review of this, see Alexei Entin's "Maximal Ideals in Commutative Rings and the Axiom of Choice" (<fr:link href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.18351" type="external">arXiv:2404.18351</fr:link>).</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
